Title: If It Ain't Funky
Artist(s): Chuck Brown and the Soul Searchers
Comment: DC has its own genre of funk called go-go. Although the heyday is long past, there was a political scuffle over it a couple years ago when a luxury apartment developer built apartments over a store that'd been blasting go-go music for decades. Well, tenants made noise complaints and the store turned off the music. Protests of "Don't Mute DC" sprang up, Mayor Bowser sided with them to score election points, and the store turned the go-go back on.

Title: Jacob's Ladder
Comment:
POV: a fast-moving storm is about to roll in then ebb out.

11/4 is used to represent stormclouds and 13/4 represents "Jacob's Ladder", the beams of light that break through after. Rush constructed this song with a cinematic view in mind (think of Sublime-type romantic landscape oil paintings), starting with the music and then adding a few lyrics later to drive the point home.

Come on, Jared was basically requesting a Rush song from me with this prompt. Cut me some slack.

Title: Un Dia Mas en la Vida
Comment: For the children, the arrival of the circus is magical and exciting. For the circus workers, it's just "un dia mas en la vida." Learn the days of the week as the kids excitedly count down to the weekend when they can go see the show, or from the circus workers' perspective, to just another performance. To me, the idea to just keep truckin' is a neutral song. There's some lovely imagery with an "old and tired lion, passing the day curled up next to the magician" too.

Title: Darling Dear
Comment: James Jamerson was the house bassist at Motown records in the late sixties to early seventies. Though his career was relatively short, he played on hundreds of huge records and had a distinct style that has continued to be hugely influential. His style of busy, always-changing baselines that complemented the melody with a great countermelody was such a hit that Motown & others would have to bring in other players and ask them to imitate his style since he couldn‚Äôt possibly play on every record.
